{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17623139","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17623139"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:08:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:08:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16833"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16833","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16833"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.66,0.03,0.28,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9524"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76658"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9524","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9524"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16833"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62155"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5927"},{"type":"tags","id":"7242"},{"type":"tags","id":"10317"},{"type":"tags","id":"10334"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22499"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22501"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76658","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76658"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe conus medullaris is the terminal portion of the spinal cord, located at the level of the T12-L1 vertebrae. Damage to this region produces a characteristic pattern of neurological deficits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the typical pattern of neurological findings in conus medullaris syndrome?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Asymmetrical lower motor neurone signs with gradual onset","Symmetrical lower motor neurone signs with acute onset","Asymmetrical upper motor neurone signs with acute onset","Symmetrical upper motor neurone signs with gradual onset","Unilateral lower motor neurone signs with acute onset"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EConus medullaris syndrome results from damage to the terminal portion of the spinal cord (conus) at the level of T12-L1. Understanding the pattern of neurological findings is crucial for distinguishing it from cauda equina syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESymmetrical lower motor neurone signs with acute onset\u003C/strong\u003E is the characteristic presentation of conus medullaris syndrome. The symmetry occurs because the lesion affects the conus itself, where nerve roots are packed closely together. Symptoms typically develop rapidly and include bilateral saddle anaesthesia, early bladder and bowel dysfunction, and symmetrical lower extremity weakness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAsymmetrical lower motor neurone signs with gradual onset\u003C/strong\u003E is more typical of cauda equina syndrome, where nerve roots are affected below the conus. The asymmetry occurs because individual nerve roots can be affected differently.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAsymmetrical upper motor neurone signs with acute onset\u003C/strong\u003E would suggest a higher spinal cord lesion rather than a conus medullaris lesion. Upper motor neurone signs include increased tone and reflexes, which are not features of conus medullaris syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESymmetrical upper motor neurone signs with gradual onset\u003C/strong\u003E would suggest a progressive myelopathy above the level of the conus, such as cervical spondylotic myelopathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUnilateral lower motor neurone signs with acute onset\u003C/strong\u003E would be more consistent with a single nerve root compression or peripheral nerve lesion rather than conus medullaris syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Conus medullaris syndrome presents with symmetrical lower motor neuron signs at the level of S2-S4.","The key distinguishing features between conus medullaris and cauda equina syndromes are symmetry and rapidity of onset.","Early recognition of conus medullaris syndrome is crucial as outcomes are better with early surgical intervention."],"references":["Vaishya S, Pojskic M, Bedi MS, Oertel J, Sippl C, Robertson S, Zygourakis C. Cauda equina, conus medullaris and syndromes mimicking sciatic pain: WFNS spine committee recommendations. World Neurosurg X. 2024 Feb 10;22:100274. doi: 10.1016/j.wnsx.2024.100274. PMID: 38496349; PMCID: PMC10943478.","Harrop JS, Hunt GE Jr, Vaccaro AR. Conus medullaris and cauda equina syndrome as a result of traumatic injuries: management principles. Neurosurg Focus. 2004 Jun 15;16(6):e4. doi: 10.3171/foc.2004.16.6.4. PMID: 15202874.","Rider LS, Marra EM. Cauda Equina and Conus Medullaris Syndromes. 2023 Aug 7. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725885."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62155"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16833"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62155","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62155"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-03T20:27:07+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-03T20:29:32+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9524"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76658"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"32","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/32"},"attrib